AB  -  Introduction: Preterm birth, which burdens 10% of births globally, is related to later cardiovascular disease (CVD) in women. We sought to determine whether risk factors included in the atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease risk score predict preterm, early or extremely preterm birth. Methods: Using a cohort of mothers who delivered singleton births in California from 2009 to 2010, 868 patients were randomly selected and divided between fullterm (n = 457) and preterm (n = 411), with fortification for extremely preterm (<32 weeks, n = 162). We employed logistic regression analysis in unadjusted and multivariable adjusted models to study the association between maternal CVD risk factors identified from hospital and clinic records [including age, race/ethnicity, smoking status, hypertension (chronic, gestational, and pre‐eclampsia), diabetes, and hyperlipidemia (based on total cholesterol, HDL, LDL, and triglycerides quartiles) measured in the first trimester] and preterm birth outcomes. Separate models considered the following outcomes: preterm (all births <37 weeks), early preterm (32‐36 weeks), and extremely preterm (20‐31 weeks) compared to fullterm (>37 weeks). Results: (see table) Conclusions: The traditional CVD risk factors of hypertension and diabetes are significantly associated with an increased risk of preterm birth with higher risks for early and extremely preterm; additionally, a significant dose response was noted for total cholesterol and LDL in early and extremely preterm births. Our findings reinforce the clinical importance of integrating obstetric and cardiovascular risk assessment across the healthcare continuum in women.
UR  -  https://www.cochranelibrary.com/central/doi/10.1002/central/CN-01935773/full
