AB  -  Background Preeclampsia (PE) is a systematic disease of pregnancy characterized by hypertension and proteinuria developing after 20th week of pregnancy and it is estimated that affects 3‐5% of pregnancies worldwide. It is generally accepted that no single marker can provide sufficient accuracy for the prediction of PE. The interest of research is focused on the combination of biochemical and ultrasound markers and maternal characteristics into multiparametric models. The purpose of our study was to evaluate the effectiveness of screening models for the prediction of preeclampsia combining neutrophil gelatinase‐associated lipocalin (NGAL) with other markers in the first and/or second trimester of pregnancy. Methods From a total of 541 women prospectively enrolled pregnant women at 11+0 to 13+6 and 20+1 to 25+6 weeks, in this case‐control study we included all 12 singleton pregnancies that developed PE and 47 randomly selected singleton normal pregnancies. Maternal characteristics, uterine artery pulsatility index (UtA‐PI), ductus venous pulsatility index (DV‐PI) and serum biomarkers including NGAL, pregnancy‐associated plasma protein‐A (PAPP‐A), placental growth factor (PlGF), soluble fms‐like tyrosine kinase 1 (sFlt‐1), were recorded and evaluated. Forward conditional stepwise logistic regression method was used for the selection of the most effective predictors (risk factors). Results The combination of NGAL and body mass index (BMI) in the 1st trimester detected 70% of preeclamptic pregnancies with 93.5% specificity (p=0.001). Including UtA‐PI and DV‐PI in this model, sensitivity reached 77.8% with 96.6% specificity (p=0.004). The combination of the 2nd trimester NGAL with s‐Flt‐1/PLGF ratio yield 100% specificity (p=0.001). The combination of the 2nd trimester UtA‐PI with 1st trimester NGAL, BMI and age detected 80% of PE with 91.9% specificity (p=0.001). The inclusion of PAPP‐A didn't improve any of the above models. Conclusion The combination of NGAL with maternal characteristics and Doppler parameters in the 1st and/or 2nd trimester can detect a consistent number of preeclamptic pregnancies. NGAL seems to be a very potent biomarker already from the first trimester and improves regression models detecting PE. NGAL in combination with sFlt‐1 / PLGF ratio in the second trimester yielded an excellent specificity of 100%.
