AB  -  OBJECTIVE: The ACOG Task Force on hypertension in pregnancy recommended prospective clinical research on uric acid (UA) as a biomarker for adverse outcomes, given its ease and low cost. It also drew attention to the importance of hypertension or preeclampsia in the postpartum period. Our objective was to determine if antepartum elevated UA is associated with immediate postpartum hypertension (PP HTN) in women without underlying chronic hypertension (CHTN). STUDY DESIGN: This is a secondary analysis of a randomized trial of low dose aspirin to prevent preeclampsia. The parent trial enrolled women at 13‐26 weeks gestation with one of the following risk factors: pre‐gestational diabetes, CHTN, multiple gestation, or history of preeclampsia. Our analysis included women with singleton or multiple gestation who had an antepartum UA level recorded. Women with CHTN were excluded. We compared those with elevated UA (defined as ≥ 5.2 mg/dL) to those with normal UA (defined as < 5.2mg/dL). The value utilized was the highest of all antepartum and intrapartum UA results. Multivariable logistic regression analysis was conducted, after controlling for confounder variables, to determine the association of elevated UA with immediate PP HTN, defined as systolic blood pressure (BP) ≥ 150 mmHg, or diastolic BP ≥ 100 mmHg (the level at which antihypertensive medication is suggested by the ACOG Task Force). RESULTS: Of the 2,503 women in the parent trial, 556 met criteria for inclusion in this analysis. After adjustment, a UA level ≥ 5.2 mg/dL was associated with immediate PP HTN (adjusted odds ratio [aOR] 2.44, 95% confidence interval [CI] 1.63‐3.64). Other variables associated with immediate PP HTN were non‐Hispanic black (versus non‐Hispanic white; aOR 1.59, 95% CI 1.01‐2.50) and obesity (aOR 2.39, 95% CI 1.47‐3.87). The association between hyperuricemia and PP HTN was stronger among overweight (aOR 2.93, 95% CI 1.42‐6.05) and obese women (aOR 4.96, 95% CI 2.35‐ 10.49). CONCLUSION: Antepartum hyperuricemia is associated with immediate PP HTN. This association was even more pronounced among obese women. Elevated uric acid may help identify women who would benefit from additional surveillance or treatment in the immediate postpartum period and may aid in risk‐stratifying women in regard to the Task Force recommendations.
