AB  -  Introduction To determine; (i) the performance of the Fetal Medicine Foundation (FMF) pre‐eclampsia screening test in placental disease prediction in low‐risk nulliparous women, and (ii) which components of the test are best predictors. Methods 546 nulliparous women were randomized to; (1) 75 mg aspirin from 11‐14 weeks, (2) no aspirin and (3) aspirin depending on the result of the screening test. It was only in group 3 that results were prospectively revealed with the remainder calculated retrospectively. Screening test components included (i) maternal history e.g. ovulation induced conception, ethnicity (ii) mean arterial blood pressure (MAP), (ii) PAPP‐A and PLGF and (iii) uterine artery Doppler pulsatility index. Results Of 546 women, the overall rate of placental disease was 15%, with a rate of any pre‐eclampsia 4.2% (n = 23) early onset pre‐eclampsia 0.4% (n = 2) and birthweight <10th centile 10.4% (n = 57). The sensitivity and specificity for the FMF test in detecting pre‐eclampsia <42 weeks was 0.7 (0.46‐0.87) and 0.06 (0.04‐0.08) with an area under the curve (AUC) of 0.70. Preeclampsia prediction for individual groups is demonstrated in Figure 1. In terms of placental disease prediction sensitivities and specificities were 0.94 (0.91‐0.95) and 0.06 (0.05‐0.09) with and AUC of 0.66. The presence of maternal risk factors and MAP at booking >88 mmHg were the only significant predictors of placental disease. Conclusion The FMF screening test performs only moderately well in nulliparous women. Maternal history and MAP in early pregnancy are the only markers, which appear to perform optimally in their detection of placental disease.
