AB  -  Objective to study the efficacy of aspirin in prevention of adverse pregnancy outcomes in women with elevated mid trimester AFP. Design Randomised clinical trial. Method This study was conducted in a total of 170 singleton pregnant women with elevated mid trimester AFP >=1.5 MoM between 14 and 16 weeks of gestation. They were assigned randomly to receive either low dose aspirin of 80 mg (N = 85) or control (N = 85). The measured adverse pregnancy outcomes were maternal outcomes (gestational hypertension, preeclampsia, eclampsia, abruptio placenta and miscarriage) and perinatal outcomes (intrauterine growth restriction, intrauterine fetal death, preterm delivery, low birth weight, APGAR score at five minutes, admission to neonatal intensive care unit and early neonatal death). Data collection was done by completing the proforma and data analysis was done by statistical software, SPSS version 16. Chi square test, fisher exact test and relative risk with 95% CI were used for comparison of outcomes between two groups. Number need to treat was calculated and P value of < 0.05 was considered as level of significance. Results The majority of the patients in this study were between 20 and 34 years. Mean BMI of the patients was 24.7(2.7) kg/m2 in the study group and 25.4(3.2) kg/m2 in control group (P = 0.212). Gravida distribution was not different significantly (P = 0.490). Thus maternal characteristics of the two group were comparable. The overall adverse pregnancy outcomes in the study group and control group were 24.7% and 48.2% respectively (RR = 0.572, 95% CI 0.39, 0.84, P = 0.002). The prevalence of preeclampsia was 5.9% and 18.1% in the study and control group respectively (RR = 0.469, 95%CI 0.22, 1.02, P = 0.017). Apart from significant reduction in preeclampsia, the other adverse pregnancy outcomes were not reduced significantly though there was some reduction in their risk. Number need to treat to prevent one adverse pregnancy outcome was 4.3 with ARR of 23.5%. Conclusion Low dose aspirin treatment starting between 14 and 16 weeks of gestation to prevent adverse pregnancy outcomes in women with elevated mid trimester AFP could be an effective treatment. Although there was significant reduction in preeclampsia, the study could not show the efficacy of aspirin in prevention of other adverse pregnancy outcomes. Therefore, more studies with larger sample size should be conducted in order to get more significant and representative data. Since combination with other serum markers is better than AFP alone in prediction of adverse pregnancy outcomes, study with combined serum markers is advisable.
