AB  -  Objectives: Placental growth factor (PlGF) has high diagnostic accuracy for predicting pre‐eclampsia, significantly reducing severe maternal adverse outcomes and time to diagnosis. This study aimed to determine whether repeat PlGF‐based testing reduces adverse perinatal outcomes in women with suspected pre‐eclampsia. Methods: In this randomised controlled trial undertaken in 22 maternity units, we compared repeat revealed PlGF‐based testing with usual care with repeat concealed testing in women with suspected pre‐eclampsia at 22+0‐and 35+6‐weeks' gestation. The primary outcome was a perinatal composite of stillbirth, early neonatal death, or neonatal unit admission. Results: Between December 2019 and September 2022, 1,253 women were recruited. Of those, 626 were allocated to repeat revealed PlGF‐based testing and 627 to usual care with repeat concealed PlGF‐based testing. There was no significant difference in the primary outcome between the revealed testing group (31.2%) compared to the concealed testing group (27.8%, relative risk 1.21; 95% CI, 0.95‐1.33; p = 0.18). In the repeat revealed testing group (compared to the concealed testing group), there was a significant reduction in gestational age at delivery (36.7 versus 37.1 weeks, ‐0.40; ‐0.68 to ‐0.12; p = 0.005); there was an increase in the number of participants giving birth before 34 weeks' gestation (14.4% versus 8.8%; 1.63 CI, 1.19‐2.24; p = 0.002) and an increase in caesarean birth (68.3% versus 59.9%; 1.14 CI, 1.05‐1.23; p = 0.002). Conclusions: Repeat PlGF‐based testing in women with suspected pre‐eclampsia was not associated with improved perinatal outcomes. In this population in a high‐income setting, with a low prevalence of adverse outcomes, routine repeat PlGF‐based testing of all individuals with suspected pre‐eclampsia is not recommended.
UR  -  https://www.cochranelibrary.com/central/doi/10.1002/central/CN-02973136/full
