AB  -  Placental growth factor (PlGF) has high diagnostic accuracy for predicting pre‐eclampsia needing delivery, significantly reducing severe maternal adverse outcomes and time to diagnosis. The clinical benefit of repeat PlGF‐based testing is unclear. Objectives: To determine whether repeat PlGF‐based testing reduces adverse perinatal outcomes, in women with suspected preterm pre‐eclampsia. Methods: In this randomised controlled trial in 22 maternity units across England, Scotland, and Wales, we compared repeat revealed PlGF‐based testing with repeat concealed testing, alongside usual care, in women with suspected pre‐eclampsia between 22 + 0‐and 35 + 6‐weeks’ gestation. Primary outcome was a perinatal composite of stillbirth, early neonatal death, or neonatal unit admission. Results: Between December 2019, and September, 2022, 1253 women were randomised. 626 were allocated to repeat revealed PlGF‐based testing and 627 to usual care with repeat concealed PlGF‐based testing. There was no evidence of a significant difference in the primary outcome between the revealed testing group (31.2 %) compared to the concealed testing group (27.8 %, relative risk 1.21; 95 % CI 0.95‐1.33; p = 0.18). In the revealed testing group (compared to the concealed testing group), there was a significant reduction in gestational age at delivery (36.7 vs 37.1 weeks’ gestation, −0.40; −0.68 to −0.12; p = 0.005); an increase in preterm birth before 34 weeks’ gestation (14.4 % vs 8.8 %; 1.63; 1.19–2.24; p = 0.002) and an increase in caesarean birth (68.3 % vs 59.9 %; 1.14; 1.05–1.23; p = 0.002). Conclusion: Repeat PlGF‐based testing in women with suspected pre‐eclampsia was not associated with improved perinatal outcomes. In this population, in a high income setting with low prevalence of adverse outcomes, routine repeat PlGF‐based testing of all individuals with suspected pre‐eclampsia is not recommended. Keywords: Pre‐eclampsia, angiogenic biomarkers, placental growth factor, soluble fms‐like tyrosine kinase 1, repeat testing.
