AB  -  OBJECTIVE: To evaluate the ability of clinical risk factors and exam findings present at admission to predict preterm delivery (PTB) in women admitted with threatened late preterm labor (PTL). STUDY DESIGN: Secondary analysis of a multicenter RCT of women with singleton, non‐anomalous pregnancies at 34+0/7 ‐ 36+5/7 weeks' gestation at high risk for PTB who were randomized to receive antenatal corticosteroids or placebo. We included women enrolled due to spontaneous PTL w/intact membranes (≥6 contractions/ hour &amp; either cervical dilation ≥3 cm or effacement ≥75%). We excluded women with severe preeclampsia and nonreassuring fetal status at randomization, and those with a postnatal diagnosis of a major fetal anomaly. Women delivering preterm <37 weeks were compared to those delivering at term ≥37 weeks. We calculated a statistical cut point optimizing the sensitivity and specificity of initial cervical dilation and effacement in predicting PTB. Multivariable regression models were used to identify risk factors independently associated with late PTB. RESULTS: 733 (26%) of 2831 randomized subjects met inclusion criteria. Of these, 432 (59%) delivered preterm (median 36.0, IQR 35.1‐36.4 weeks) and 301 (41%) delivered at term (median 38.0, IQR 37.4‐38.7 weeks). Table 1 compares maternal characteristics between preterm and term births. A cervical dilation cutoff ≥4cm was 60% sensitive and 68% specific for PTB (AUC = 0.64, 95% CI 0.61 ‐ 0.68). A cervical effacement cutoff ≥75% was 59% sensitive and 65% specific for PTB (AUC = 0.62, 95% CI 0.58 ‐ 0.65). In regression models, several clinical factors present at admission remained associated with late PTB (Table 2). The final model improved prediction of PTB (82% sensitivity, 48% specificity, AUC 0.72, 95% CI 0.68‐0.76), p<0.001 compared to cervical exam‐only models. CONCLUSION: 41% of women presenting with frequent uterine contractions and cervical dilation and/or effacement 34+0‐36+5 weeks delivered at term. Though initial cervical exam alone had poor sensitivity and specificity for PTB, consideration of other clinical factors (including parity and gestational age) improved PTB prediction. However, even the best models are only fair in their predictive ability, reinforcing current recommendations to administer late preterm steroids to eligible women in this high risk group. (Table Presented).
